        <trans-unit id="153" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source><bpt id="p1">[</bpt><ph id="ph1">\&lt;</ph>Type&gt;<ept id="p1">](../../../docs/framework/net-native/type-element-net-native.md)</ept></source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="154" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Applies reflection policy to a type and all its members.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="155" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Remarks</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="156" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The <ph id="ph1">`&lt;Subtypes&gt;`</ph> element applies policy to all the subtypes of its containing type.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="157" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>You use it when you want to apply different policies to derived types and their base classes.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="158" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The reflection, serialization, and interop attributes are all optional, although at least one should be present.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="159" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Example</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="160" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following example defines a class named <ph id="ph1">`BaseClass`</ph> and a subclass named <ph id="ph2">`Derived1`</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="161" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source><bpt id="p1">[!code-csharp</bpt><bpt id="p2">[</bpt>ProjectN_Reflection#4<ept id="p2">](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/projectn_reflection/cs/subtypes.cs#4)</ept><ept id="p1">]</ept></source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="162" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>As shown in the following code, the runtime directives file explicitly sets the <ph id="ph1">`Dynamic`</ph> and <ph id="ph2">`Activate`</ph> policies for <ph id="ph3">`BaseClass`</ph> to <ph id="ph4">`Excluded`</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="163" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Because of this, objects of type <ph id="ph1">`BaseClass`</ph> cannot be instantiated dynamically or by calls to the <ph id="ph2">`BaseClass`</ph> class constructor.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="164" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>However, the <ph id="ph1">`&lt;Subtypes&gt;`</ph> element allows classes derived from <ph id="ph2">`BaseClass`</ph> to be instantiated dynamically and through calls to their class constructors.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="165" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Because of the <ph id="ph1">`&lt;Subtypes&gt;`</ph> directive, the following code that instantiates a <ph id="ph2">`Derived1`</ph> instance dynamically by calling the <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Activator.CreateInstance%28System.Type%29?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph> method executes successfully.</source>
        </trans-unit>
